47// The ArmDebugger class is used by the simulator while debugging simulated ARM
48// code.
49class ArmDebugger {
50 public:
51 explicit ArmDebugger(Simulator* sim) : sim_(sim) {}
52 void Debug();
53 bool ExecDebugCommand(ArrayUniquePtr<char> line_ptr);
54
55 private:
56 static const Instr kBreakpointInstr =
57 (al | (7 * B25) | (1 * B24) | kBreakpoint);
58 static const Instr kNopInstr = (al | (13 * B21));
59
60 Simulator* sim_;
61
62 int32_t GetRegisterValue(int regnum);
63 double GetRegisterPairDoubleValue(int regnum);
64 double GetVFPDoubleRegisterValue(int regnum);
65 bool GetValue(const char* desc, int32_t* value);
66 bool GetVFPSingleValue(const char* desc, float* value);
67 bool GetVFPDoubleValue(const char* desc, double* value);
68
69 // Set or delete breakpoint (there can be only one).
70 bool SetBreakpoint(Instruction* breakpc);
71 void DeleteBreakpoint();
72
73 // Undo and redo the breakpoint. This is needed to bracket disassembly and
74 // execution to skip past the breakpoint when run from the debugger.
75 void UndoBreakpoint();
76 void RedoBreakpoint();
77};

79void Simulator::DebugAtNextPC() {
80 PrintF("Starting debugger on the next instruction:\n");
81 set_pc(get_pc() + kInstrSize);
82 ArmDebugger(this).Debug();

85void Simulator::AdvancedSIMDElementOrStructureLoadStoreWriteback(int Rn, int Rm,
86 int ebytes) {
87 if (Rm != 15) {
88 if (Rm == 13) {
89 set_register(Rn, get_register(Rn) + ebytes);
90 } else {
91 set_register(Rn, get_register(Rn) + get_register(Rm));
92 }
93 }

96int32_t ArmDebugger::GetRegisterValue(int regnum) {
97 if (regnum == kPCRegister) {
98 return sim_->get_pc();
99 } else {
100 return sim_->get_register(regnum);
101 }
102}

104double ArmDebugger::GetRegisterPairDoubleValue(int regnum) {
105 return sim_->get_double_from_register_pair(regnum);
106}
107
108double ArmDebugger::GetVFPDoubleRegisterValue(int regnum) {
109 return sim_->get_double_from_d_register(regnum).get_scalar();
110}

112bool ArmDebugger::GetValue(const char* desc, int32_t* value) {
113 int regnum = Registers::Number(desc);
114 if (regnum != kNoRegister) {
115 *value = GetRegisterValue(regnum);
116 return true;
117 }
118 if (strncmp(desc, "0x", 2) == 0)
119 return SScanF(desc + 2, "%x", reinterpret_cast<uint32_t*>(value)) == 1;
120 return SScanF(desc, "%u", reinterpret_cast<uint32_t*>(value)) == 1;
121}
122
123bool ArmDebugger::GetVFPSingleValue(const char* desc, float* value) {
124 bool is_double;
125 int regnum = VFPRegisters::Number(desc, &is_double);
126 if (regnum != kNoRegister && !is_double) {
127 *value = sim_->get_float_from_s_register(regnum).get_scalar();
128 return true;
129 }
130 return false;
131}
132
133bool ArmDebugger::GetVFPDoubleValue(const char* desc, double* value) {
134 bool is_double;
135 int regnum = VFPRegisters::Number(desc, &is_double);
136 if (regnum != kNoRegister && is_double) {
137 *value = sim_->get_double_from_d_register(regnum).get_scalar();
138 return true;
139 }
140 return false;
141}

143bool ArmDebugger::SetBreakpoint(Instruction* breakpc) {
144 // Check if a breakpoint can be set. If not return without any side-effects.
145 if (sim_->break_pc_ != nullptr) {
146 return false;
147 }
148
149 // Set the breakpoint.
150 sim_->break_pc_ = breakpc;
151 sim_->break_instr_ = breakpc->InstructionBits();
152 // Not setting the breakpoint instruction in the code itself. It will be set
153 // when the debugger shell continues.
154 return true;
155}

158// This function is dangerous, but it's only available in non-production
159// (simulator) builds.
160void SetInstructionBitsInCodeSpace(Instruction* instr, Instr value,
161 Heap* heap) {
162 CodePageMemoryModificationScopeForDebugging scope(
163 MemoryChunkMetadata::FromAddress(reinterpret_cast<Address>(instr)));
164 instr->SetInstructionBits(value);
165}
166} // namespace

168void ArmDebugger::DeleteBreakpoint() {
169 UndoBreakpoint();
170 sim_->break_pc_ = nullptr;
171 sim_->break_instr_ = 0;
172}
173
174void ArmDebugger::UndoBreakpoint() {
175 if (sim_->break_pc_ != nullptr) {
176 SetInstructionBitsInCodeSpace(sim_->break_pc_, sim_->break_instr_,
177 sim_->isolate_->heap());
178 }
179}
180
181void ArmDebugger::RedoBreakpoint() {
182 if (sim_->break_pc_ != nullptr) {
183 SetInstructionBitsInCodeSpace(sim_->break_pc_, kBreakpointInstr,
184 sim_->isolate_->heap());
185 }
186}

188void ArmDebugger::Debug() {
189 if (v8_flags.correctness_fuzzer_suppressions) {
190 PrintF("Debugger disabled for differential fuzzing.\n");
191 return;
192 }
193 intptr_t last_pc = -1;
194 bool done = false;
195
196 // Unset breakpoint while running in the debugger shell, making it invisible
197 // to all commands.
198 UndoBreakpoint();
199
200 while (!done && !sim_->has_bad_pc()) {
201 if (last_pc != sim_->get_pc()) {
202 disasm::NameConverter converter;
203 disasm::Disassembler dasm(converter);
204 // use a reasonably large buffer
205 v8::base::EmbeddedVector<char, 256> buffer;
206 dasm.InstructionDecode(buffer,
207 reinterpret_cast<uint8_t*>(sim_->get_pc()));
208 PrintF(" 0x%08x %s\n", sim_->get_pc(), buffer.begin());
209 last_pc = sim_->get_pc();
210 }
211 ArrayUniquePtr<char> line(ReadLine("sim> "));
212
213 done = ExecDebugCommand(std::move(line));
214 }
215
216 // Reinstall breakpoint to stop execution and enter the debugger shell when
217 // hit.
218 RedoBreakpoint();
219}

221bool ArmDebugger::ExecDebugCommand(ArrayUniquePtr<char> line_ptr) {
222#define COMMAND_SIZE 63
223#define ARG_SIZE 255
224
225#define STR(a) #a
226#define XSTR(a) STR(a)
227
228 char cmd[COMMAND_SIZE + 1];
229 char arg1[ARG_SIZE + 1];
230 char arg2[ARG_SIZE + 1];
231 char* argv[3] = {cmd, arg1, arg2};
232
233 // make sure to have a proper terminating character if reaching the limit
234 cmd[COMMAND_SIZE] = 0;
235 arg1[ARG_SIZE] = 0;
236 arg2[ARG_SIZE] = 0;
237
238 if (line_ptr == nullptr) return true;
239
240 // Repeat last command by default.
241 const char* line = line_ptr.get();
242 const char* last_input = sim_->last_debugger_input();
243 if (strcmp(line, "\n") == 0 && (last_input != nullptr)) {
244 line_ptr.reset();
245 line = last_input;
246 } else {
247 // Update the latest command ran
248 sim_->set_last_debugger_input(std::move(line_ptr));
249 }
250
251 // Use sscanf to parse the individual parts of the command line. At the
252 // moment no command expects more than two parameters.
253 int argc = SScanF(line,
254 "%" XSTR(COMMAND_SIZE) "s "
255 "%" XSTR(ARG_SIZE) "s "
256 "%" XSTR(ARG_SIZE) "s",
257 cmd, arg1, arg2);
258 if ((strcmp(cmd, "si") == 0) || (strcmp(cmd, "stepi") == 0)) {
259 sim_->InstructionDecode(reinterpret_cast<Instruction*>(sim_->get_pc()));
260 } else if ((strcmp(cmd, "c") == 0) || (strcmp(cmd, "cont") == 0)) {
261 // Execute the one instruction we broke at with breakpoints disabled.
262 sim_->InstructionDecode(reinterpret_cast<Instruction*>(sim_->get_pc()));
263 // Leave the debugger shell.
264 return true;
265 } else if ((strcmp(cmd, "p") == 0) || (strcmp(cmd, "print") == 0)) {
266 if (argc == 2 || (argc == 3 && strcmp(arg2, "fp") == 0)) {
267 int32_t value;
268 float svalue;
269 double dvalue;
270 if (strcmp(arg1, "all") == 0) {
271 for (int i = 0; i < kNumRegisters; i++) {
272 value = GetRegisterValue(i);
273 PrintF("%3s: 0x%08x %10d", RegisterName(Register::from_code(i)),
274 value, value);
275 if ((argc == 3 && strcmp(arg2, "fp") == 0) && i < 8 && (i % 2) == 0) {
276 dvalue = GetRegisterPairDoubleValue(i);
277 PrintF(" (%f)\n", dvalue);
278 } else {
279 PrintF("\n");
280 }
281 }
282 for (int i = 0; i < DwVfpRegister::SupportedRegisterCount(); i++) {
283 dvalue = GetVFPDoubleRegisterValue(i);
284 uint64_t as_words = base::bit_cast<uint64_t>(dvalue);
285 PrintF("%3s: %f 0x%08x %08x\n", VFPRegisters::Name(i, true), dvalue,
286 static_cast<uint32_t>(as_words >> 32),
287 static_cast<uint32_t>(as_words & 0xFFFFFFFF));
288 }
289 } else {
290 if (GetValue(arg1, &value)) {
291 PrintF("%s: 0x%08x %d \n", arg1, value, value);
292 } else if (GetVFPSingleValue(arg1, &svalue)) {
293 uint32_t as_word = base::bit_cast<uint32_t>(svalue);
294 PrintF("%s: %f 0x%08x\n", arg1, svalue, as_word);
295 } else if (GetVFPDoubleValue(arg1, &dvalue)) {
296 uint64_t as_words = base::bit_cast<uint64_t>(dvalue);
297 PrintF("%s: %f 0x%08x %08x\n", arg1, dvalue,
298 static_cast<uint32_t>(as_words >> 32),
299 static_cast<uint32_t>(as_words & 0xFFFFFFFF));
300 } else {
301 PrintF("%s unrecognized\n", arg1);
302 }
303 }
304 } else {
305 PrintF("print <register>\n");
306 }
307 } else if ((strcmp(cmd, "po") == 0) || (strcmp(cmd, "printobject") == 0)) {
308 if (argc == 2) {
309 int32_t value;
310 StdoutStream os;
311 if (GetValue(arg1, &value)) {
312 Tagged<Object> obj(value);
313 os << arg1 << ": \n";
314#ifdef DEBUG
315 Print(obj, os);
316 os << "\n";
317#else
318 os << Brief(obj) << "\n";
319#endif
320 } else {
321 os << arg1 << " unrecognized\n";
322 }
323 } else {
324 PrintF("printobject <value>\n");
325 }
326 } else if (strcmp(cmd, "stack") == 0 || strcmp(cmd, "mem") == 0 ||
327 strcmp(cmd, "dump") == 0) {
328 int32_t* cur = nullptr;
329 int32_t* end = nullptr;
330 int next_arg = 1;
331
332 if (strcmp(cmd, "stack") == 0) {
333 cur = reinterpret_cast<int32_t*>(sim_->get_register(Simulator::sp));
334 } else { // "mem"
335 int32_t value;
336 if (!GetValue(arg1, &value)) {
337 PrintF("%s unrecognized\n", arg1);
338 return false;
339 }
340 cur = reinterpret_cast<int32_t*>(value);
341 next_arg++;
342 }
343
344 int32_t words;
345 if (argc == next_arg) {
346 words = 10;
347 } else {
348 if (!GetValue(argv[next_arg], &words)) {
349 words = 10;
350 }
351 }
352 end = cur + words;
353
354 bool skip_obj_print = (strcmp(cmd, "dump") == 0);
355 while (cur < end) {
356 PrintF(" 0x%08" V8PRIxPTR ": 0x%08x %10d",
357 reinterpret_cast<intptr_t>(cur), *cur, *cur);
358 Tagged<Object> obj(*cur);
359 Heap* current_heap = sim_->isolate_->heap();
360 if (!skip_obj_print) {
361 if (IsSmi(obj) ||
362 IsValidHeapObject(current_heap, Cast<HeapObject>(obj))) {
363 PrintF(" (");
364 if (IsSmi(obj)) {
365 PrintF("smi %d", Smi::ToInt(obj));
366 } else {
367 ShortPrint(obj);
368 }
369 PrintF(")");
370 }
371 }
372 PrintF("\n");
373 cur++;
374 }
375 } else if (strcmp(cmd, "disasm") == 0 || strcmp(cmd, "di") == 0) {
376 disasm::NameConverter converter;
377 disasm::Disassembler dasm(converter);
378 // use a reasonably large buffer
379 v8::base::EmbeddedVector<char, 256> buffer;
380
381 uint8_t* prev = nullptr;
382 uint8_t* cur = nullptr;
383 uint8_t* end = nullptr;
384
385 if (argc == 1) {
386 cur = reinterpret_cast<uint8_t*>(sim_->get_pc());
387 end = cur + (10 * kInstrSize);
388 } else if (argc == 2) {
389 int regnum = Registers::Number(arg1);
390 if (regnum != kNoRegister || strncmp(arg1, "0x", 2) == 0) {
391 // The argument is an address or a register name.
392 int32_t value;
393 if (GetValue(arg1, &value)) {
394 cur = reinterpret_cast<uint8_t*>(value);
395 // Disassemble 10 instructions at <arg1>.
396 end = cur + (10 * kInstrSize);
397 }
398 } else {
399 // The argument is the number of instructions.
400 int32_t value;
401 if (GetValue(arg1, &value)) {
402 cur = reinterpret_cast<uint8_t*>(sim_->get_pc());
403 // Disassemble <arg1> instructions.
404 end = cur + (value * kInstrSize);
405 }
406 }
407 } else {
408 int32_t value1;
409 int32_t value2;
410 if (GetValue(arg1, &value1) && GetValue(arg2, &value2)) {
411 cur = reinterpret_cast<uint8_t*>(value1);
412 end = cur + (value2 * kInstrSize);
413 }
414 }
415
416 while (cur < end) {
417 prev = cur;
418 cur += dasm.InstructionDecode(buffer, cur);
419 PrintF(" 0x%08" V8PRIxPTR " %s\n", reinterpret_cast<intptr_t>(prev),
420 buffer.begin());
421 }
422 } else if (strcmp(cmd, "gdb") == 0) {
423 PrintF("relinquishing control to gdb\n");
424 v8::base::OS::DebugBreak();
425 PrintF("regaining control from gdb\n");
426 } else if (strcmp(cmd, "break") == 0) {
427 if (argc == 2) {
428 int32_t value;
429 if (GetValue(arg1, &value)) {
430 if (!SetBreakpoint(reinterpret_cast<Instruction*>(value))) {
431 PrintF("setting breakpoint failed\n");
432 }
433 } else {
434 PrintF("%s unrecognized\n", arg1);
435 }
436 } else {
437 PrintF("break <address>\n");
438 }
439 } else if (strcmp(cmd, "backtrace") == 0 || strcmp(cmd, "bt") == 0) {
440 int32_t pc = sim_->get_pc();
441 int32_t lr = sim_->get_register(Simulator::lr);
442 int32_t sp = sim_->get_register(Simulator::sp);
443 int32_t fp = sim_->get_register(Simulator::fp);
444
445 int i = 0;
446 while (true) {
447 PrintF("#%d: 0x%08x (sp=0x%08x, fp=0x%08x)\n", i, pc, sp, fp);
448 pc = lr;
449 sp = fp;
450 if (pc == Simulator::end_sim_pc) {
451 break;
452 }
453 lr = *(reinterpret_cast<int32_t*>(fp) + 1);
454 fp = *reinterpret_cast<int32_t*>(fp);
455 i++;
456 if (i > 100) {
457 PrintF("Too many frames\n");
458 break;
459 }
460 }
461 } else if (strcmp(cmd, "del") == 0) {
462 DeleteBreakpoint();
463 } else if (strcmp(cmd, "flags") == 0) {
464 PrintF("N flag: %d; ", sim_->n_flag_);
465 PrintF("Z flag: %d; ", sim_->z_flag_);
466 PrintF("C flag: %d; ", sim_->c_flag_);
467 PrintF("V flag: %d\n", sim_->v_flag_);
468 PrintF("INVALID OP flag: %d; ", sim_->inv_op_vfp_flag_);
469 PrintF("DIV BY ZERO flag: %d; ", sim_->div_zero_vfp_flag_);
470 PrintF("OVERFLOW flag: %d; ", sim_->overflow_vfp_flag_);
471 PrintF("UNDERFLOW flag: %d; ", sim_->underflow_vfp_flag_);
472 PrintF("INEXACT flag: %d;\n", sim_->inexact_vfp_flag_);
473 } else if (strcmp(cmd, "stop") == 0) {
474 int32_t value;
475 intptr_t stop_pc = sim_->get_pc() - kInstrSize;
476 Instruction* stop_instr = reinterpret_cast<Instruction*>(stop_pc);
477 if ((argc == 2) && (strcmp(arg1, "unstop") == 0)) {
478 // Remove the current stop.
479 if (stop_instr->IsStop()) {
480 SetInstructionBitsInCodeSpace(stop_instr, kNopInstr,
481 sim_->isolate_->heap());
482 } else {
483 PrintF("Not at debugger stop.\n");
484 }
485 } else if (argc == 3) {
486 // Print information about all/the specified breakpoint(s).
487 if (strcmp(arg1, "info") == 0) {
488 if (strcmp(arg2, "all") == 0) {
489 PrintF("Stop information:\n");
490 for (uint32_t i = 0; i < sim_->kNumOfWatchedStops; i++) {
491 sim_->PrintStopInfo(i);
492 }
493 } else if (GetValue(arg2, &value)) {
494 sim_->PrintStopInfo(value);
495 } else {
496 PrintF("Unrecognized argument.\n");
497 }
498 } else if (strcmp(arg1, "enable") == 0) {
499 // Enable all/the specified breakpoint(s).
500 if (strcmp(arg2, "all") == 0) {
501 for (uint32_t i = 0; i < sim_->kNumOfWatchedStops; i++) {
502 sim_->EnableStop(i);
503 }
504 } else if (GetValue(arg2, &value)) {
505 sim_->EnableStop(value);
506 } else {
507 PrintF("Unrecognized argument.\n");
508 }
509 } else if (strcmp(arg1, "disable") == 0) {
510 // Disable all/the specified breakpoint(s).
511 if (strcmp(arg2, "all") == 0) {
512 for (uint32_t i = 0; i < sim_->kNumOfWatchedStops; i++) {
513 sim_->DisableStop(i);
514 }
515 } else if (GetValue(arg2, &value)) {
516 sim_->DisableStop(value);
517 } else {
518 PrintF("Unrecognized argument.\n");
519 }
520 }
521 } else {
522 PrintF("Wrong usage. Use help command for more information.\n");
523 }
524 } else if ((strcmp(cmd, "t") == 0) || strcmp(cmd, "trace") == 0) {
525 sim_->ToggleInstructionTracing();
526 PrintF("Trace of executed instructions is %s\n",
527 sim_->InstructionTracingEnabled() ? "on" : "off");
528 } else if ((strcmp(cmd, "h") == 0) || (strcmp(cmd, "help") == 0)) {
529 PrintF("cont\n");
530 PrintF(" continue execution (alias 'c')\n");
531 PrintF("stepi\n");
532 PrintF(" step one instruction (alias 'si')\n");
533 PrintF("print <register>\n");
534 PrintF(" print register content (alias 'p')\n");
535 PrintF(" use register name 'all' to print all registers\n");
536 PrintF(" add argument 'fp' to print register pair double values\n");
537 PrintF("printobject <register>\n");
538 PrintF(" print an object from a register (alias 'po')\n");
539 PrintF("flags\n");
540 PrintF(" print flags\n");
541 PrintF("stack [<words>]\n");
542 PrintF(" dump stack content, default dump 10 words)\n");
543 PrintF("mem <address> [<words>]\n");
544 PrintF(" dump memory content, default dump 10 words)\n");
545 PrintF("dump [<words>]\n");
546 PrintF(
547 " dump memory content without pretty printing JS objects, default "
548 "dump 10 words)\n");
549 PrintF("disasm [<instructions>]\n");
550 PrintF("disasm [<address/register>]\n");
551 PrintF("disasm [[<address/register>] <instructions>]\n");
552 PrintF(" disassemble code, default is 10 instructions\n");
553 PrintF(" from pc (alias 'di')\n");
554 PrintF("gdb\n");
555 PrintF(" enter gdb\n");
556 PrintF("break <address>\n");
557 PrintF(" set a break point on the address\n");
558 PrintF("backtrace / bt\n");
559 PrintF(" Walk the frame pointers, dumping the pc/sp/fp for each frame.\n");
560 PrintF("del\n");
561 PrintF(" delete the breakpoint\n");
562 PrintF("trace (alias 't')\n");
563 PrintF(" toogle the tracing of all executed statements\n");
564 PrintF("stop feature:\n");
565 PrintF(" Description:\n");
566 PrintF(" Stops are debug instructions inserted by\n");
567 PrintF(" the Assembler::stop() function.\n");
568 PrintF(" When hitting a stop, the Simulator will\n");
569 PrintF(" stop and give control to the ArmDebugger.\n");
570 PrintF(" The first %d stop codes are watched:\n",
571 Simulator::kNumOfWatchedStops);
572 PrintF(" - They can be enabled / disabled: the Simulator\n");
573 PrintF(" will / won't stop when hitting them.\n");
574 PrintF(" - The Simulator keeps track of how many times they \n");
575 PrintF(" are met. (See the info command.) Going over a\n");
576 PrintF(" disabled stop still increases its counter. \n");
577 PrintF(" Commands:\n");
578 PrintF(" stop info all/<code> : print infos about number <code>\n");
579 PrintF(" or all stop(s).\n");
580 PrintF(" stop enable/disable all/<code> : enables / disables\n");
581 PrintF(" all or number <code> stop(s)\n");
582 PrintF(" stop unstop\n");
583 PrintF(" ignore the stop instruction at the current location\n");
584 PrintF(" from now on\n");
585 } else {
586 PrintF("Unknown command: %s\n", cmd);
587 }
588 return false;

603bool Simulator::ICacheMatch(void* one, void* two) {
604 DCHECK_EQ(reinterpret_cast<intptr_t>(one) & CachePage::kPageMask, 0);
605 DCHECK_EQ(reinterpret_cast<intptr_t>(two) & CachePage::kPageMask, 0);
606 return one == two;
607}
608
609static uint32_t ICacheHash(void* key) {
610 return static_cast<uint32_t>(reinterpret_cast<uintptr_t>(key)) >> 2;
611}
612
613static bool AllOnOnePage(uintptr_t start, int size) {
614 intptr_t start_page = (start & ~CachePage::kPageMask);
615 intptr_t end_page = ((start + size) & ~CachePage::kPageMask);
616 return start_page == end_page;
617}

619void Simulator::SetRedirectInstruction(Instruction* instruction) {
620 instruction->SetInstructionBits(al | (0xF * B24) | kCallRtRedirected);
621}

623void Simulator::FlushICache(base::CustomMatcherHashMap* i_cache,
624 void* start_addr, size_t size) {
625 intptr_t start = reinterpret_cast<intptr_t>(start_addr);
626 int intra_line = (start & CachePage::kLineMask);
627 start -= intra_line;
628 size += intra_line;
629 size = ((size - 1) | CachePage::kLineMask) + 1;
630 int offset = (start & CachePage::kPageMask);
631 while (!AllOnOnePage(start, size - 1)) {
632 int bytes_to_flush = CachePage::kPageSize - offset;
633 FlushOnePage(i_cache, start, bytes_to_flush);
634 start += bytes_to_flush;
635 size -= bytes_to_flush;
636 DCHECK_EQ(0, start & CachePage::kPageMask);
637 offset = 0;
638 }
639 if (size != 0) {
640 FlushOnePage(i_cache, start, size);
641 }
642}
643
644CachePage* Simulator::GetCachePage(base::CustomMatcherHashMap* i_cache,
645 void* page) {
646 base::HashMap::Entry* entry = i_cache->LookupOrInsert(page, ICacheHash(page));
647 if (entry->value == nullptr) {
648 CachePage* new_page = new CachePage();
649 entry->value = new_page;
650 }
651 return reinterpret_cast<CachePage*>(entry->value);
652}
653
654// Flush from start up to and not including start + size.
655void Simulator::FlushOnePage(base::CustomMatcherHashMap* i_cache,
656 intptr_t start, int size) {
657 DCHECK_LE(size, CachePage::kPageSize);
658 DCHECK(AllOnOnePage(start, size - 1));
659 DCHECK_EQ(start & CachePage::kLineMask, 0);
660 DCHECK_EQ(size & CachePage::kLineMask, 0);
661 void* page = reinterpret_cast<void*>(start & (~CachePage::kPageMask));
662 int offset = (start & CachePage::kPageMask);
663 CachePage* cache_page = GetCachePage(i_cache, page);
664 char* valid_bytemap = cache_page->ValidityByte(offset);
665 memset(valid_bytemap, CachePage::LINE_INVALID, size >> CachePage::kLineShift);
666}
667
668void Simulator::CheckICache(base::CustomMatcherHashMap* i_cache,
669 Instruction* instr) {
670 intptr_t address = reinterpret_cast<intptr_t>(instr);
671 void* page = reinterpret_cast<void*>(address & (~CachePage::kPageMask));
672 void* line = reinterpret_cast<void*>(address & (~CachePage::kLineMask));
673 int offset = (address & CachePage::kPageMask);
674 CachePage* cache_page = GetCachePage(i_cache, page);
675 char* cache_valid_byte = cache_page->ValidityByte(offset);
676 bool cache_hit = (*cache_valid_byte == CachePage::LINE_VALID);
677 char* cached_line = cache_page->CachedData(offset & ~CachePage::kLineMask);
678 if (cache_hit) {
679 // Check that the data in memory matches the contents of the I-cache.
680 CHECK_EQ(0, memcmp(reinterpret_cast<void*>(instr),
681 cache_page->CachedData(offset), kInstrSize));
682 } else {
683 // Cache miss. Load memory into the cache.
684 memcpy(cached_line, line, CachePage::kLineLength);
685 *cache_valid_byte = CachePage::LINE_VALID;
686 }
687}
688
689Simulator::Simulator(Isolate* isolate) : isolate_(isolate) {
690 // Set up simulator support first. Some of this information is needed to
691 // setup the architecture state.
692 stack_ = reinterpret_cast<uint8_t*>(base::Malloc(kAllocatedStackSize));
693 pc_modified_ = false;
694 icount_ = 0;
695 break_pc_ = nullptr;
696 break_instr_ = 0;
697
698 // Set up architecture state.
699 // All registers are initialized to zero to start with.
700 for (int i = 0; i < num_registers; i++) {
701 registers_[i] = 0;
702 }
703 n_flag_ = false;
704 z_flag_ = false;
705 c_flag_ = false;
706 v_flag_ = false;
707
708 // Initializing VFP registers.
709 // All registers are initialized to zero to start with
710 // even though s_registers_ & d_registers_ share the same
711 // physical registers in the target.
712 for (int i = 0; i < num_d_registers * 2; i++) {
713 vfp_registers_[i] = 0;
714 }
715 n_flag_FPSCR_ = false;
716 z_flag_FPSCR_ = false;
717 c_flag_FPSCR_ = false;
718 v_flag_FPSCR_ = false;
719 FPSCR_rounding_mode_ = RN;
720 FPSCR_default_NaN_mode_ = false;
721
722 inv_op_vfp_flag_ = false;
723 div_zero_vfp_flag_ = false;
724 overflow_vfp_flag_ = false;
725 underflow_vfp_flag_ = false;
726 inexact_vfp_flag_ = false;
727
728 // The sp is initialized to point to the bottom (high address) of the
729 // usable stack area.
730 registers_[sp] = reinterpret_cast<int32_t>(stack_) + kUsableStackSize;
731 // The lr and pc are initialized to a known bad value that will cause an
732 // access violation if the simulator ever tries to execute it.
733 registers_[pc] = bad_lr;
734 registers_[lr] = bad_lr;
735
736 last_debugger_input_ = nullptr;
737}
738
739Simulator::~Simulator() {
740 GlobalMonitor::Get()->RemoveProcessor(&global_monitor_processor_);
741 base::Free(stack_);
742}

744// Get the active Simulator for the current thread.
745Simulator* Simulator::current(Isolate* isolate) {
746 v8::internal::Isolate::PerIsolateThreadData* isolate_data =
747 isolate->FindOrAllocatePerThreadDataForThisThread();
748 DCHECK_NOT_NULL(isolate_data);
749
750 Simulator* sim = isolate_data->simulator();
751 if (sim == nullptr) {
752 // TODO(146): delete the simulator object when a thread/isolate goes away.
753 sim = new Simulator(isolate);
754 isolate_data->set_simulator(sim);
755 }
756 return sim;
757}

759// Sets the register in the architecture state. It will also deal with updating
760// Simulator internal state for special registers such as PC.
761void Simulator::set_register(int reg, int32_t value) {
762 DCHECK((reg >= 0) && (reg < num_registers));
763 if (reg == pc) {
764 pc_modified_ = true;
765 }
766 registers_[reg] = value;
767}

769// Get the register from the architecture state. This function does handle
770// the special case of accessing the PC register.
771int32_t Simulator::get_register(int reg) const {
772 DCHECK((reg >= 0) && (reg < num_registers));
773 // Stupid code added to avoid bug in GCC.
774 // See: http://gcc.gnu.org/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=43949
775 if (reg >= num_registers) return 0;
776 // End stupid code.
777 return registers_[reg] + ((reg == pc) ? Instruction::kPcLoadDelta : 0);
778}

780double Simulator::get_double_from_register_pair(int reg) {
781 DCHECK((reg >= 0) && (reg < num_registers) && ((reg % 2) == 0));
782
783 double dm_val = 0.0;
784 // Read the bits from the unsigned integer register_[] array
785 // into the double precision floating point value and return it.
786 char buffer[2 * sizeof(vfp_registers_[0])];
787 memcpy(buffer, &registers_[reg], 2 * sizeof(registers_[0]));
788 memcpy(&dm_val, buffer, 2 * sizeof(registers_[0]));
789 return (dm_val);
790}

792void Simulator::set_register_pair_from_double(int reg, double* value) {
793 DCHECK((reg >= 0) && (reg < num_registers) && ((reg % 2) == 0));
794 memcpy(registers_ + reg, value, sizeof(*value));
795}

863template <class InputType, int register_size>
864void Simulator::SetVFPRegister(int reg_index, const InputType& value) {
865 unsigned bytes = register_size * sizeof(vfp_registers_[0]);

878 DCHECK_EQ(sizeof(ReturnType), bytes);

880 if (register_size == 1) DCHECK(reg_index < num_s_registers);
881 if (register_size == 2)
882 DCHECK(reg_index < DwVfpRegister::SupportedRegisterCount());
883
884 ReturnType value;
885 memcpy(&value, &vfp_registers_[register_size * reg_index], bytes);
886 return value;

888
889void Simulator::SetSpecialRegister(SRegisterFieldMask reg_and_mask,
890 uint32_t value) {
891 // Only CPSR_f is implemented. Of that, only N, Z, C and V are implemented.
892 if ((reg_and_mask == CPSR_f) && ((value & ~kSpecialCondition) == 0)) {
893 n_flag_ = ((value & (1 << 31)) != 0);
894 z_flag_ = ((value & (1 << 30)) != 0);
895 c_flag_ = ((value & (1 << 29)) != 0);
896 v_flag_ = ((value & (1 << 28)) != 0);
897 } else {
898 UNIMPLEMENTED();
899 }
900}
901
902uint32_t Simulator::GetFromSpecialRegister(SRegister reg) {
903 uint32_t result = 0;
904 // Only CPSR_f is implemented.
905 if (reg == CPSR) {
906 if (n_flag_) result |= (1 << 31);
907 if (z_flag_) result |= (1 << 30);
908 if (c_flag_) result |= (1 << 29);
909 if (v_flag_) result |= (1 << 28);
910 } else {
911 UNIMPLEMENTED();
912 }
913 return result;
914}
915
916// Runtime FP routines take:
917// - two double arguments
918// - one double argument and zero or one integer arguments.
919// All are consructed here from r0-r3 or d0, d1 and r0.
920void Simulator::GetFpArgs(double* x, double* y, int32_t* z) {
921 if (use_eabi_hardfloat()) {
922 *x = get_double_from_d_register(0).get_scalar();
923 *y = get_double_from_d_register(1).get_scalar();
924 *z = get_register(0);
925 } else {
926 // Registers 0 and 1 -> x.
927 *x = get_double_from_register_pair(0);
928 // Register 2 and 3 -> y.
929 *y = get_double_from_register_pair(2);
930 // Register 2 -> z
931 *z = get_register(2);
932 }
933}
934
935// The return value is either in r0/r1 or d0.
936void Simulator::SetFpResult(const double& result) {
937 if (use_eabi_hardfloat()) {
938 char buffer[2 * sizeof(vfp_registers_[0])];
939 memcpy(buffer, &result, sizeof(buffer));
940 // Copy result to d0.
941 memcpy(vfp_registers_, buffer, sizeof(buffer));
942 } else {
943 char buffer[2 * sizeof(registers_[0])];
944 memcpy(buffer, &result, sizeof(buffer));
945 // Copy result to r0 and r1.
946 memcpy(registers_, buffer, sizeof(buffer));
947 }
948}

950void Simulator::TrashCallerSaveRegisters() {
951 // Return registers.
952 registers_[0] = 0x50BAD4U;
953 registers_[1] = 0x50BAD4U;
954 // Caller-saved registers.
955 registers_[2] = 0x50BAD4U;
956 registers_[3] = 0x50BAD4U;
957 registers_[12] = 0x50BAD4U;
958 // This value is a NaN in both 32-bit and 64-bit FP.
959 static const uint64_t v = 0x7ff000007f801000UL;
960 // d0 - d7 are caller-saved.
961 for (int i = 0; i < 8; i++) {
962 set_d_register(i, &v);
963 }
964 if (DoubleRegister::SupportedRegisterCount() > 16) {
965 // d16 - d31 (if supported) are caller-saved.
966 for (int i = 16; i < 32; i++) {
967 set_d_register(i, &v);
968 }
969 }
970}

1144// Returns the limit of the stack area to enable checking for stack overflows.
1145uintptr_t Simulator::StackLimit(uintptr_t c_limit) const {
1146 // The simulator uses a separate JS stack. If we have exhausted the C stack,
1147 // we also drop down the JS limit to reflect the exhaustion on the JS stack.
1148 if (base::Stack::GetCurrentStackPosition() < c_limit) {
1149 return reinterpret_cast<uintptr_t>(get_sp());
1150 }
1151
1152 // Otherwise the limit is the JS stack. Leave a safety margin to prevent
1153 // overrunning the stack when pushing values.
1154 return reinterpret_cast<uintptr_t>(stack_) + kAdditionalStackMargin;
1155}
1156
1157base::Vector<uint8_t> Simulator::GetCentralStackView() const {
1158 // We do not add an additional safety margin as above in
1159 // Simulator::StackLimit, as this is currently only used in wasm::StackMemory,
1160 // which adds its own margin.
1161 return base::VectorOf(stack_, kUsableStackSize);
1162}

1170
1171// Checks if the current instruction should be executed based on its
1172// condition bits.
1173bool Simulator::ConditionallyExecute(Instruction* instr) {
1174 switch (instr->ConditionField()) {
1175 case eq:
1176 return z_flag_;
1177 case ne:
1178 return !z_flag_;
1179 case cs:
1180 return c_flag_;
1181 case cc:
1182 return !c_flag_;
1183 case mi:
1184 return n_flag_;
1185 case pl:
1186 return !n_flag_;
1187 case vs:
1188 return v_flag_;
1189 case vc:
1190 return !v_flag_;
1191 case hi:
1192 return c_flag_ && !z_flag_;
1193 case ls:
1194 return !c_flag_ || z_flag_;
1195 case ge:
1196 return n_flag_ == v_flag_;
1197 case lt:
1198 return n_flag_ != v_flag_;
1199 case gt:
1200 return !z_flag_ && (n_flag_ == v_flag_);
1201 case le:
1202 return z_flag_ || (n_flag_ != v_flag_);
1203 case al:
1204 return true;
1205 default:
1206 UNREACHABLE();
1207 }
1208}

1210// Calculate and set the Negative and Zero flags.
1211void Simulator::SetNZFlags(int32_t val) {
1212 n_flag_ = (val < 0);
1213 z_flag_ = (val == 0);
1214}

1219// Set the oVerflow flag.

1221
1222// Calculate C flag value for additions.
1223bool Simulator::CarryFrom(int32_t left, int32_t right, int32_t carry) {
1224 uint32_t uleft = static_cast<uint32_t>(left);
1225 uint32_t uright = static_cast<uint32_t>(right);
1226 uint32_t urest = 0xFFFFFFFFU - uleft;
1227
1228 return (uright > urest) ||
1229 (carry && (((uright + 1) > urest) || (uright > (urest - 1))));
1230}
1231
1232// Calculate C flag value for subtractions.
1233bool Simulator::BorrowFrom(int32_t left, int32_t right, int32_t carry) {
1234 uint32_t uleft = static_cast<uint32_t>(left);
1235 uint32_t uright = static_cast<uint32_t>(right);
1236
1237 return (uright > uleft) ||
1238 (!carry && (((uright + 1) > uleft) || (uright > (uleft - 1))));
1239}
1240
1241// Calculate V flag value for additions and subtractions.
1242bool Simulator::OverflowFrom(int32_t alu_out, int32_t left, int32_t right,
1243 bool addition) {
1244 bool overflow;
1245 if (addition) {
1246 // operands have the same sign
1247 overflow = ((left >= 0 && right >= 0) || (left < 0 && right < 0))
1248 // and operands and result have different sign
1249 && ((left < 0 && alu_out >= 0) || (left >= 0 && alu_out < 0));
1250 } else {
1251 // operands have different signs
1252 overflow = ((left < 0 && right >= 0) || (left >= 0 && right < 0))
1253 // and first operand and result have different signs
1254 && ((left < 0 && alu_out >= 0) || (left >= 0 && alu_out < 0));
1255 }
1256 return overflow;
1257}

1259// Support for VFP comparisons.
1260void Simulator::Compute_FPSCR_Flags(float val1, float val2) {
1261 if (std::isnan(val1) || std::isnan(val2)) {
1262 n_flag_FPSCR_ = false;
1263 z_flag_FPSCR_ = false;
1264 c_flag_FPSCR_ = true;
1265 v_flag_FPSCR_ = true;
1266 // All non-NaN cases.
1267 } else if (val1 == val2) {
1268 n_flag_FPSCR_ = false;
1269 z_flag_FPSCR_ = true;
1270 c_flag_FPSCR_ = true;
1271 v_flag_FPSCR_ = false;
1272 } else if (val1 < val2) {
1273 n_flag_FPSCR_ = true;
1274 z_flag_FPSCR_ = false;
1275 c_flag_FPSCR_ = false;
1276 v_flag_FPSCR_ = false;
1277 } else {
1278 // Case when (val1 > val2).
1279 n_flag_FPSCR_ = false;
1280 z_flag_FPSCR_ = false;
1281 c_flag_FPSCR_ = true;
1282 v_flag_FPSCR_ = false;
1283 }
1284}

1286void Simulator::Compute_FPSCR_Flags(double val1, double val2) {
1287 if (std::isnan(val1) || std::isnan(val2)) {
1288 n_flag_FPSCR_ = false;
1289 z_flag_FPSCR_ = false;
1290 c_flag_FPSCR_ = true;
1291 v_flag_FPSCR_ = true;
1292 // All non-NaN cases.
1293 } else if (val1 == val2) {
1294 n_flag_FPSCR_ = false;
1295 z_flag_FPSCR_ = true;
1296 c_flag_FPSCR_ = true;
1297 v_flag_FPSCR_ = false;
1298 } else if (val1 < val2) {

1300 z_flag_FPSCR_ = false;

1319// Addressing Mode 1 - Data-processing operands:
1320// Get the value based on the shifter_operand with register.
1321int32_t Simulator::GetShiftRm(Instruction* instr, bool* carry_out) {
1322 ShiftOp shift = instr->ShiftField();
1323 int shift_amount = instr->ShiftAmountValue();
1324 int32_t result = get_register(instr->RmValue());
1325 if (instr->Bit(4) == 0) {
1326 // by immediate
1327 if ((shift == ROR) && (shift_amount == 0)) {
1328 UNIMPLEMENTED();
1329 } else if (((shift == LSR) || (shift == ASR)) && (shift_amount == 0)) {
1330 shift_amount = 32;
1331 }
1332 switch (shift) {
1333 case ASR: {
1334 if (shift_amount == 0) {
1335 if (result < 0) {
1336 result = 0xFFFFFFFF;
1337 *carry_out = true;
1338 } else {
1339 result = 0;
1340 *carry_out = false;
1341 }
1342 } else {
1343 result >>= (shift_amount - 1);
1344 *carry_out = (result & 1) == 1;
1345 result >>= 1;
1346 }
1347 break;
1348 }
1349
1350 case LSL: {
1351 if (shift_amount == 0) {
1352 *carry_out = c_flag_;
1353 } else {
1354 result = static_cast<uint32_t>(result) << (shift_amount - 1);
1355 *carry_out = (result < 0);
1356 result = static_cast<uint32_t>(result) << 1;
1357 }
1358 break;
1359 }
1360
1361 case LSR: {
1362 if (shift_amount == 0) {
1363 result = 0;
1364 *carry_out = c_flag_;
1365 } else {
1366 uint32_t uresult = static_cast<uint32_t>(result);
1367 uresult >>= (shift_amount - 1);
1368 *carry_out = (uresult & 1) == 1;
1369 uresult >>= 1;
1370 result = static_cast<int32_t>(uresult);
1371 }
1372 break;
1373 }
1374
1375 case ROR: {
1376 if (shift_amount == 0) {
1377 *carry_out = c_flag_;
1378 } else {
1379 result = base::bits::RotateRight32(result, shift_amount);
1380 *carry_out = (static_cast<uint32_t>(result) >> 31) != 0;
1381 }
1382 break;
1383 }
1384
1385 default: {
1386 UNREACHABLE();
1387 }
1388 }
1389 } else {
1390 // by register
1391 int rs = instr->RsValue();
1392 shift_amount = get_register(rs) & 0xFF;
1393 switch (shift) {
1394 case ASR: {
1395 if (shift_amount == 0) {
1396 *carry_out = c_flag_;
1397 } else if (shift_amount < 32) {
1398 result >>= (shift_amount - 1);
1399 *carry_out = (result & 1) == 1;
1400 result >>= 1;
1401 } else {
1402 DCHECK_GE(shift_amount, 32);
1403 if (result < 0) {
1404 *carry_out = true;
1405 result = 0xFFFFFFFF;
1406 } else {
1407 *carry_out = false;
1408 result = 0;
1409 }
1410 }
1411 break;
1412 }
1413
1414 case LSL: {
1415 if (shift_amount == 0) {
1416 *carry_out = c_flag_;
1417 } else if (shift_amount < 32) {
1418 result = static_cast<uint32_t>(result) << (shift_amount - 1);
1419 *carry_out = (result < 0);
1420 result = static_cast<uint32_t>(result) << 1;
1421 } else if (shift_amount == 32) {
1422 *carry_out = (result & 1) == 1;
1423 result = 0;
1424 } else {
1425 DCHECK_GT(shift_amount, 32);
1426 *carry_out = false;
1427 result = 0;
1428 }
1429 break;
1430 }
1431
1432 case LSR: {
1433 if (shift_amount == 0) {
1434 *carry_out = c_flag_;
1435 } else if (shift_amount < 32) {
1436 uint32_t uresult = static_cast<uint32_t>(result);
1437 uresult >>= (shift_amount - 1);
1438 *carry_out = (uresult & 1) == 1;
1439 uresult >>= 1;
1440 result = static_cast<int32_t>(uresult);
1441 } else if (shift_amount == 32) {
1442 *carry_out = (result < 0);
1443 result = 0;
1444 } else {
1445 *carry_out = false;
1446 result = 0;
1447 }
1448 break;
1449 }
1450
1451 case ROR: {
1452 if (shift_amount == 0) {
1453 *carry_out = c_flag_;
1454 } else {
1455 // Avoid undefined behavior. Rotating by multiples of 32 is no-op.
1456 result = base::bits::RotateRight32(result, shift_amount & 31);
1457 *carry_out = (static_cast<uint32_t>(result) >> 31) != 0;
1458 }
1459 break;
1460 }
1461
1462 default: {
1463 UNREACHABLE();
1464 }
1465 }
1466 }
1467 return result;
1468}
1469
1470// Addressing Mode 1 - Data-processing operands:
1471// Get the value based on the shifter_operand with immediate.
1472int32_t Simulator::GetImm(Instruction* instr, bool* carry_out) {
1473 int rotate = instr->RotateValue() * 2;
1474 int immed8 = instr->Immed8Value();
1475 int imm = base::bits::RotateRight32(immed8, rotate);
1476 *carry_out = (rotate == 0) ? c_flag_ : (imm < 0);
1477 return imm;
1478}
1479
1480static int count_bits(int bit_vector) {
1481 int count = 0;
1482 while (bit_vector != 0) {
1483 if ((bit_vector & 1) != 0) {
1484 count++;
1485 }
1486 bit_vector >>= 1;
1487 }
1488 return count;
1489}
1490
1491int32_t Simulator::ProcessPU(Instruction* instr, int num_regs, int reg_size,
1492 intptr_t* start_address, intptr_t* end_address) {
1493 int rn = instr->RnValue();
1494 int32_t rn_val = get_register(rn);
1495 switch (instr->PUField()) {
1496 case da_x: {
1497 UNIMPLEMENTED();
1498 }
1499 case ia_x: {
1500 *start_address = rn_val;
1501 *end_address = rn_val + (num_regs * reg_size) - reg_size;
1502 rn_val = rn_val + (num_regs * reg_size);
1503 break;
1504 }
1505 case db_x: {
1506 *start_address = rn_val - (num_regs * reg_size);
1507 *end_address = rn_val - reg_size;
1508 rn_val = *start_address;
1509 break;
1510 }
1511 case ib_x: {
1512 *start_address = rn_val + reg_size;
1513 *end_address = rn_val + (num_regs * reg_size);
1514 rn_val = *end_address;
1515 break;
1516 }
1517 default: {
1518 UNREACHABLE();
1519 }
1520 }
1521 return rn_val;
1522}
1523
1524// Addressing Mode 4 - Load and Store Multiple
1525void Simulator::HandleRList(Instruction* instr, bool load) {
1526 int rlist = instr->RlistValue();
1527 int num_regs = count_bits(rlist);
1528
1529 intptr_t start_address = 0;
1530 intptr_t end_address = 0;
1531 int32_t rn_val =
1532 ProcessPU(instr, num_regs, kPointerSize, &start_address, &end_address);
1533
1534 intptr_t* address = reinterpret_cast<intptr_t*>(start_address);
1535 // Catch null pointers a little earlier.
1536 DCHECK(start_address > 8191 || start_address < 0);
1537 int reg = 0;
1538 while (rlist != 0) {
1539 if ((rlist & 1) != 0) {
1540 if (load) {
1541 set_register(reg, *address);
1542 } else {
1543 *address = get_register(reg);
1544 }
1545 address += 1;
1546 }
1547 reg++;
1548 rlist >>= 1;
1549 }
1550 DCHECK(end_address == ((intptr_t)address) - 4);
1551 if (instr->HasW()) {
1552 set_register(instr->RnValue(), rn_val);
1553 }
1554}
1555
1556// Addressing Mode 6 - Load and Store Multiple Coprocessor registers.
1557void Simulator::HandleVList(Instruction* instr) {
1558 VFPRegPrecision precision =
1559 (instr->SzValue() == 0) ? kSinglePrecision : kDoublePrecision;
1560 int operand_size = (precision == kSinglePrecision) ? 4 : 8;
1561
1562 bool load = (instr->VLValue() == 0x1);
1563
1564 int vd;
1565 int num_regs;
1566 vd = instr->VFPDRegValue(precision);
1567 if (precision == kSinglePrecision) {
1568 num_regs = instr->Immed8Value();
1569 } else {
1570 num_regs = instr->Immed8Value() / 2;
1571 }
1572
1573 intptr_t start_address = 0;
1574 intptr_t end_address = 0;
1575 int32_t rn_val =
1576 ProcessPU(instr, num_regs, operand_size, &start_address, &end_address);
1577
1578 intptr_t* address = reinterpret_cast<intptr_t*>(start_address);
1579 for (int reg = vd; reg < vd + num_regs; reg++) {
1580 if (precision == kSinglePrecision) {
1581 if (load) {
1582 set_s_register_from_sinteger(reg,
1583 ReadW(reinterpret_cast<int32_t>(address)));
1584 } else {
1585 WriteW(reinterpret_cast<int32_t>(address),
1586 get_sinteger_from_s_register(reg));
1587 }
1588 address += 1;
1589 } else {
1590 if (load) {
1591 int32_t data[] = {ReadW(reinterpret_cast<int32_t>(address)),
1592 ReadW(reinterpret_cast<int32_t>(address + 1))};
1593 set_d_register(reg, reinterpret_cast<uint32_t*>(data));
1594 } else {
1595 uint32_t data[2];
1596 get_d_register(reg, data);
1597 WriteW(reinterpret_cast<int32_t>(address), data[0]);
1598 WriteW(reinterpret_cast<int32_t>(address + 1), data[1]);
1599 }
1600 address += 2;
1601 }
1602 }
1603 DCHECK(reinterpret_cast<intptr_t>(address) - operand_size == end_address);
1604 if (instr->HasW()) {
1605 set_register(instr->RnValue(), rn_val);
1606 }
1607}
1608
1609// Calls into the V8 runtime are based on this very simple interface.
1610// Note: To be able to return two values from some calls the code in runtime.cc
1611// uses the ObjectPair which is essentially two 32-bit values stuffed into a
1612// 64-bit value. With the code below we assume that all runtime calls return
1613// 64 bits of result. If they don't, the r1 result register contains a bogus
1614// value, which is fine because it is caller-saved.
1615using SimulatorRuntimeCall = int64_t (*)(
1616 int32_t arg0, int32_t arg1, int32_t arg2, int32_t arg3, int32_t arg4,
1617 int32_t arg5, int32_t arg6, int32_t arg7, int32_t arg8, int32_t arg9,
1618 int32_t arg10, int32_t arg11, int32_t arg12, int32_t arg13, int32_t arg14,
1619 int32_t arg15, int32_t arg16, int32_t arg17, int32_t arg18, int32_t arg19);
1620
1621// These prototypes handle the four types of FP calls.
1622using SimulatorRuntimeCompareCall = int64_t (*)(double darg0, double darg1);
1623using SimulatorRuntimeFPFPCall = double (*)(double darg0, double darg1);
1624using SimulatorRuntimeFPCall = double (*)(double darg0);
1625using SimulatorRuntimeFPIntCall = double (*)(double darg0, int32_t arg0);
1626// Define four args for future flexibility; at the time of this writing only
1627// one is ever used.
1628using SimulatorRuntimeFPTaggedCall = double (*)(int32_t arg0, int32_t arg1,
1629 int32_t arg2, int32_t arg3);
1630
1631// This signature supports direct call in to API function native callback
1632// (refer to InvocationCallback in v8.h).
1633using SimulatorRuntimeDirectApiCall = void (*)(int32_t arg0);
1634
1635// This signature supports direct call to accessor getter callback.
1636using SimulatorRuntimeDirectGetterCall = void (*)(int32_t arg0, int32_t arg1);
1637
1638// Separate for fine-grained UBSan blocklisting. Casting any given C++
1639// function to {SimulatorRuntimeCall} is undefined behavior; but since
1640// the target function can indeed be any function that's exposed via
1641// the "fast C call" mechanism, we can't reconstruct its signature here.
1642int64_t UnsafeGenericFunctionCall(intptr_t function, int32_t arg0, int32_t arg1,
1643 int32_t arg2, int32_t arg3, int32_t arg4,
1644 int32_t arg5, int32_t arg6, int32_t arg7,
1645 int32_t arg8, int32_t arg9, int32_t arg10,
1646 int32_t arg11, int32_t arg12, int32_t arg13,
1647 int32_t arg14, int32_t arg15, int32_t arg16,
1648 int32_t arg17, int32_t arg18, int32_t arg19) {
1649 SimulatorRuntimeCall target =
1650 reinterpret_cast<SimulatorRuntimeCall>(function);
1651 return target(arg0, arg1, arg2, arg3, arg4, arg5, arg6, arg7, arg8, arg9,
1652 arg10, arg11, arg12, arg13, arg14, arg15, arg16, arg17, arg18,
1653 arg19);
1654}

1656// Software interrupt instructions are used by the simulator to call into the
1657// C-based V8 runtime.
1658void Simulator::SoftwareInterrupt(Instruction* instr) {
1659 int svc = instr->SvcValue();
1660 switch (svc) {
1661 case kCallRtRedirected: {
1662 // Check if stack is aligned. Error if not aligned is reported below to
1663 // include information on the function called.
1664 bool stack_aligned =
1665 (get_register(sp) & (v8_flags.sim_stack_alignment - 1)) == 0;
1666 Redirection* redirection = Redirection::FromInstruction(instr);
1667 int32_t arg0 = get_register(r0);
1668 int32_t arg1 = get_register(r1);
1669 int32_t arg2 = get_register(r2);
1670 int32_t arg3 = get_register(r3);
1671 int32_t* stack_pointer = reinterpret_cast<int32_t*>(get_register(sp));
1672 int32_t arg4 = stack_pointer[0];
1673 int32_t arg5 = stack_pointer[1];
1674 int32_t arg6 = stack_pointer[2];
1675 int32_t arg7 = stack_pointer[3];
1676 int32_t arg8 = stack_pointer[4];
1677 int32_t arg9 = stack_pointer[5];
1678 int32_t arg10 = stack_pointer[6];
1679 int32_t arg11 = stack_pointer[7];
1680 int32_t arg12 = stack_pointer[8];
1681 int32_t arg13 = stack_pointer[9];
1682 int32_t arg14 = stack_pointer[10];
1683 int32_t arg15 = stack_pointer[11];
1684 int32_t arg16 = stack_pointer[12];
1685 int32_t arg17 = stack_pointer[13];
1686 int32_t arg18 = stack_pointer[14];
1687 int32_t arg19 = stack_pointer[15];
1688 static_assert(kMaxCParameters == 20);
1689
1690 bool fp_call =
1691 (redirection->type() == ExternalReference::BUILTIN_FP_FP_CALL) ||
1692 (redirection->type() == ExternalReference::BUILTIN_COMPARE_CALL) ||
1693 (redirection->type() == ExternalReference::BUILTIN_FP_CALL) ||
1694 (redirection->type() == ExternalReference::BUILTIN_FP_INT_CALL);
1695 // This is dodgy but it works because the C entry stubs are never moved.
1696 // See comment in codegen-arm.cc and bug 1242173.
1697 int32_t saved_lr = get_register(lr);
1698 intptr_t external =
1699 reinterpret_cast<intptr_t>(redirection->external_function());
1700 if (fp_call) {
1701 double dval0, dval1; // one or two double parameters
1702 int32_t ival; // zero or one integer parameters
1703 int64_t iresult = 0; // integer return value
1704 double dresult = 0; // double return value
1705 GetFpArgs(&dval0, &dval1, &ival);
1706 if (InstructionTracingEnabled() || !stack_aligned) {
1707 SimulatorRuntimeCall generic_target =
1708 reinterpret_cast<SimulatorRuntimeCall>(external);
1709 switch (redirection->type()) {
1710 case ExternalReference::BUILTIN_FP_FP_CALL:
1711 case ExternalReference::BUILTIN_COMPARE_CALL:
1712 PrintF("Call to host function at %p with args %f, %f",
1713 reinterpret_cast<void*>(FUNCTION_ADDR(generic_target)),
1714 dval0, dval1);
1715 break;
1716 case ExternalReference::BUILTIN_FP_CALL:
1717 PrintF("Call to host function at %p with arg %f",
1718 reinterpret_cast<void*>(FUNCTION_ADDR(generic_target)),
1719 dval0);
1720 break;
1721 case ExternalReference::BUILTIN_FP_INT_CALL:
1722 PrintF("Call to host function at %p with args %f, %d",
1723 reinterpret_cast<void*>(FUNCTION_ADDR(generic_target)),
1724 dval0, ival);
1725 break;
1726 default:
1727 UNREACHABLE();
1728 }
1729 if (!stack_aligned) {
1730 PrintF(" with unaligned stack %08x\n", get_register(sp));
1731 }
1732 PrintF("\n");
1733 }
1734 CHECK(stack_aligned);
1735 switch (redirection->type()) {
1736 case ExternalReference::BUILTIN_COMPARE_CALL: {
1737 SimulatorRuntimeCompareCall target =
1738 reinterpret_cast<SimulatorRuntimeCompareCall>(external);
1739 iresult = target(dval0, dval1);
1740#ifdef DEBUG
1741 TrashCallerSaveRegisters();
1742#endif
1743 set_register(r0, static_cast<int32_t>(iresult));
1744 set_register(r1, static_cast<int32_t>(iresult >> 32));
1745 break;
1746 }
1747 case ExternalReference::BUILTIN_FP_FP_CALL: {
1748 SimulatorRuntimeFPFPCall target =
1749 reinterpret_cast<SimulatorRuntimeFPFPCall>(external);
1750 dresult = target(dval0, dval1);
1751#ifdef DEBUG
1752 TrashCallerSaveRegisters();
1753#endif
1754 SetFpResult(dresult);
1755 break;
1756 }
1757 case ExternalReference::BUILTIN_FP_CALL: {
1758 SimulatorRuntimeFPCall target =
1759 reinterpret_cast<SimulatorRuntimeFPCall>(external);
1760 dresult = target(dval0);
1761#ifdef DEBUG
1762 TrashCallerSaveRegisters();
1763#endif
1764 SetFpResult(dresult);
1765 break;
1766 }
1767 case ExternalReference::BUILTIN_FP_INT_CALL: {
1768 SimulatorRuntimeFPIntCall target =
1769 reinterpret_cast<SimulatorRuntimeFPIntCall>(external);
1770 dresult = target(dval0, ival);
1771#ifdef DEBUG
1772 TrashCallerSaveRegisters();
1773#endif
1774 SetFpResult(dresult);
1775 break;
1776 }
1777 default:
1778 UNREACHABLE();
1779 }
1780 if (InstructionTracingEnabled()) {
1781 switch (redirection->type()) {
1782 case ExternalReference::BUILTIN_COMPARE_CALL:
1783 PrintF("Returned %08x\n", static_cast<int32_t>(iresult));
1784 break;
1785 case ExternalReference::BUILTIN_FP_FP_CALL:
1786 case ExternalReference::BUILTIN_FP_CALL:
1787 case ExternalReference::BUILTIN_FP_INT_CALL:
1788 PrintF("Returned %f\n", dresult);
1789 break;
1790 default:
1791 UNREACHABLE();
1792 }
1793 }
1794 } else if (redirection->type() ==
1795 ExternalReference::BUILTIN_FP_POINTER_CALL) {
1796 if (InstructionTracingEnabled() || !stack_aligned) {
1797 PrintF("Call to host function at %p args %08x",
1798 reinterpret_cast<void*>(external), arg0);
1799 if (!stack_aligned) {
1800 PrintF(" with unaligned stack %08x\n", get_register(sp));
1801 }
1802 PrintF("\n");
1803 }
1804 CHECK(stack_aligned);
1805 SimulatorRuntimeFPTaggedCall target =
1806 reinterpret_cast<SimulatorRuntimeFPTaggedCall>(external);
1807 double dresult = target(arg0, arg1, arg2, arg3);
1808#ifdef DEBUG
1809 TrashCallerSaveRegisters();
1810#endif
1811 SetFpResult(dresult);
1812 if (InstructionTracingEnabled()) {
1813 PrintF("Returned %f\n", dresult);
1814 }
1815 } else if (redirection->type() == ExternalReference::DIRECT_API_CALL) {
1816 // void f(v8::FunctionCallbackInfo&)
1817 if (InstructionTracingEnabled() || !stack_aligned) {
1818 PrintF("Call to host function at %p args %08x",
1819 reinterpret_cast<void*>(external), arg0);
1820 if (!stack_aligned) {
1821 PrintF(" with unaligned stack %08x\n", get_register(sp));
1822 }
1823 PrintF("\n");
1824 }
1825 CHECK(stack_aligned);
1826 SimulatorRuntimeDirectApiCall target =
1827 reinterpret_cast<SimulatorRuntimeDirectApiCall>(external);
1828 target(arg0);
1829#ifdef DEBUG
1830 TrashCallerSaveRegisters();
1831#endif
1832 } else if (redirection->type() == ExternalReference::DIRECT_GETTER_CALL) {
1833 // void f(v8::Local<String> property, v8::PropertyCallbackInfo& info)
1834 if (InstructionTracingEnabled() || !stack_aligned) {
1835 PrintF("Call to host function at %p args %08x %08x",
1836 reinterpret_cast<void*>(external), arg0, arg1);
1837 if (!stack_aligned) {
1838 PrintF(" with unaligned stack %08x\n", get_register(sp));
1839 }
1840 PrintF("\n");
1841 }
1842 CHECK(stack_aligned);
1843 SimulatorRuntimeDirectGetterCall target =
1844 reinterpret_cast<SimulatorRuntimeDirectGetterCall>(external);
1845 target(arg0, arg1);
1846#ifdef DEBUG
1847 TrashCallerSaveRegisters();
1848#endif
1849 } else {
1850 // builtin call.
1851 // FAST_C_CALL is temporarily handled here as well, because we lack
1852 // proper support for direct C calls with FP params in the simulator.
1853 // The generic BUILTIN_CALL path assumes all parameters are passed in
1854 // the GP registers, thus supporting calling the slow callback without
1855 // crashing. The reason for that is that in the mjsunit tests we check
1856 // the `fast_c_api.supports_fp_params` (which is false on non-simulator
1857 // builds for arm/arm64), thus we expect that the slow path will be
1858 // called. And since the slow path passes the arguments as a `const
1859 // FunctionCallbackInfo<Value>&` (which is a GP argument), the call is
1860 // made correctly.
1861 DCHECK(redirection->type() == ExternalReference::BUILTIN_CALL ||
1862 redirection->type() == ExternalReference::BUILTIN_CALL_PAIR ||
1863 redirection->type() == ExternalReference::FAST_C_CALL);
1864 if (InstructionTracingEnabled() || !stack_aligned) {
1865 PrintF(
1866 "Call to host function at %p "
1867 "args %08x, %08x, %08x, %08x, %08x, %08x, %08x, %08x, %08x, "
1868 "%08x, %08x, %08x, %08x, %08x, %08x, %08x, %08x, %08x, %08x, "
1869 "%08x",
1870 reinterpret_cast<void*>(external), arg0, arg1, arg2, arg3, arg4,
1871 arg5, arg6, arg7, arg8, arg9, arg10, arg11, arg12, arg13, arg14,
1872 arg15, arg16, arg17, arg18, arg19);
1873 if (!stack_aligned) {
1874 PrintF(" with unaligned stack %08x\n", get_register(sp));
1875 }
1876 PrintF("\n");
1877 }
1878 CHECK(stack_aligned);
1879 int64_t result = UnsafeGenericFunctionCall(
1880 external, arg0, arg1, arg2, arg3, arg4, arg5, arg6, arg7, arg8,
1881 arg9, arg10, arg11, arg12, arg13, arg14, arg15, arg16, arg17, arg18,
1882 arg19);
1883#ifdef DEBUG
1884 TrashCallerSaveRegisters();
1885#endif
1886 int32_t lo_res = static_cast<int32_t>(result);
1887 int32_t hi_res = static_cast<int32_t>(result >> 32);
1888 if (InstructionTracingEnabled()) {
1889 PrintF("Returned %08x\n", lo_res);
1890 }
1891 set_register(r0, lo_res);
1892 set_register(r1, hi_res);
1893 }
1894 set_register(lr, saved_lr);
1895 set_pc(get_register(lr));
1896 break;
1897 }
1898 case kBreakpoint:
1899 ArmDebugger(this).Debug();
1900 break;
1901 // stop uses all codes greater than 1 << 23.
1902 default:
1903 if (svc >= (1 << 23)) {
1904 uint32_t code = svc & kStopCodeMask;
1905 if (isWatchedStop(code)) {
1906 IncreaseStopCounter(code);
1907 }
1908 // Stop if it is enabled, otherwise go on jumping over the stop
1909 // and the message address.
1910 if (isEnabledStop(code)) {
1911 if (code != kMaxStopCode) {
1912 PrintF("Simulator hit stop %u. ", code);
1913 } else {
1914 PrintF("Simulator hit stop. ");
1915 }
1916 DebugAtNextPC();
1917 }
1918 } else {
1919 // This is not a valid svc code.
1920 UNREACHABLE();
1921 }
1922 }
1923}
